08066nam a22007575i 9780774857741DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19821982xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748577417 a10.59962/97807748577412doi  a(DE-B1597)662322  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aVA400.R38 1982eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a35900aRCN in Retrospect, 1910-1968 /ced. by James A. Boutilier. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[1982] 4c©1982  a1 online resource (398 p.) :b105 b&w illustrations, 12 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tThe Royal Navy’s Legacy to the Royal Canadian Navy in the Pacific, 1880–1914 -- tL.P. Brodeur and the Origins of the Royal Canadian Navy -- tCommander E.A.E. Nixon and the Royal Naval College of Canada, 1910–1922 -- tThe Road to Washington: Canada and Empire Naval Defence, 1918–1921 -- tThe Royal Canadian Navy Between the Wars, 1922–39 -- t“Big Ship Time”: The Formative Years of Rcn Officers Serving in RN Capital Ships -- tAn Engineer’s Outline of Rcn History: Part I -- tPrinces Three: Canada’s Use of Armed Merchant Cruisers During World War II -- tThe Royal Canadian Navy’s Quest for Autonomy in the North West Atlantic: 1941–43 -- tRoyal Canadian Navy Participation in the Battle of the Atlantic Crisis of 1943 -- tOperational Intelligence and the Battle of the Atlantic: The Role of the Royal Navy’s Submarine Tracking Room -- t“The Most Thankless Task” Revisited: Convoys, Escorts, and Radio Intelligence in the Western Atlantic, 1941–43 -- tThe Lower Deck and the Mainguy Report of 1949 -- tThe Destroyers’ War in Korea, 1952–53 -- tCanadian Naval Aviation, 1915–69 -- tHMCS Labrador and the Canadian Arctic -- tThe Impact of Public Policy on a Naval Reserve Division -- tAn Engineer’s Outline of RCN History: Part II -- tThe Royal Canadian Navy and the Unification Crisis -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis tribute to a proud service surveys the history of the Royal Canadian Navy from its inception in 1910 to its demise in 1968. Although established as a declaration of Canada's independence from the imperial fleet, the RCN was the child of the Royal Navy. Its first ships were RN cast-offs, and for the next forty years officers trained in the British fleet -- their 'big ship time.' From these modest beginnings, the book deals with such related issues as the problem of imperial defense, the development of a naval service with a Canadian identity, and the evolution of a Canadian naval engineering capacity. Expanding dramatically during World War II, the RCN gave convoy protection which proved crucial to the Allied victory at sea. New documentation on Canada's role in the Battle of the Atlantic highlights such critical factors as: the contribution of radio intelligence to anti-submarine warfare against the deadly German 'wolfpacks'; the wartime operational relationship of the RCN to the Royal Navy and the United States Navy; and the heroic role of Canadian sailors who served under fire. Demobilization and the paying off of ships marked the postwar decline of the RCN. This decline was intensified by a series of mutinies which demonstrated the need for a less rigid, more 'democratic' relationship between officers and ratings. Despite these difficulties, the RCN served effectively in coastal operations during the Korean War and in the establishment of Canada's presence in the Arctic. The last chapter records the reaction of the RCN's senior officers to government policy during the Unification Crisis of the 1960s and their unsuccessful attempts to maintain the independent identity of the RCN. It is ironic that on the eve of achieving its greatest measure of autonomy the RCN was overwhelmed by the forces of nationalism -- the same force which had acted as a catalyst in its formation. Originally presented in 1980 at a conference on the history of the RCN, the papers in this book range from the first-hand recollections of ex-RCN personnel to the examination of previously classified documents from German and Allied archives. The RCN in Retrospect will serve to introduce many to Canada's naval heritage and will provide valuable new insights to all readers with an interest in naval history and lore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aAudette, L.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeesly, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoutilier, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoutilier, James A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBovey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrock, P. Willet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodeur, Nigel D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, A. Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, W.A.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGough, Barry M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadley, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Barry D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnox, J.H.W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeming, J.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeir, Richard H., econtributo